results.name: a(n) = Product_{d|n} A019565(d)^A010051(n/d).
link: Antti Karttunen, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..8192
example: The divisors of 30 are [1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 10, 15, 30], of which only d = 6, 10 and 15 are such that 30/d is a prime, thus a(n) = A019565(6) * A019565(10) * A019565(15) = 15 * 21 * 210 = 66150.
program: A019565(n) = {my(j,v); factorback(Mat(vector(if(n, #n=vecextract(binary(n), "-1..1")), j, [prime(j), n[j]])~))}; \\ From A019565
xref: Differs from A300832 for the first time at n=30, where a(30) = 66150, while A300832(30) = 132300.
